INSERT INTO public.courses (module, content_type, title, slug, description, body, duration_minutes, tier_required, category, sort_order, published, published_at) VALUES
(
  'hunting', 'article',
  'How to Get Your First Hunting License',
  'first-hunting-license',
  'A step-by-step guide to hunter education, licensing, and tag purchasing across all seven western states.',
  E'# How to Get Your First Hunting License\n\nIf you have never hunted before, the licensing process can feel like a maze — hunter education, base licenses, habitat stamps, draw applications, OTC tags. Every state does it differently, and the terminology alone is enough to make you close the browser tab.\n\nThis guide walks you through the entire process, step by step, for all seven western states we cover: Colorado, Montana, Wyoming, Idaho, Nevada, Utah, and Arizona.\n\n## The Four-Step Process\n\nEvery first-time hunter follows the same basic path:\n\n1. **Complete Hunter Education** — a one-time certification, valid for life, accepted in all 50 states.\n2. **Purchase a Base Hunting License** — an annual fee paid to the state where you want to hunt.\n3. **Apply for a Draw Tag or Buy an OTC Tag** — draw applications happen in spring for fall hunts; over-the-counter (OTC) tags can be bought anytime.\n4. **Purchase Required Stamps and Fees** — habitat stamps, conservation licenses, and application fees vary by state.\n\nThere is also a shortcut: most states offer an **Apprentice or Mentor License** that lets you skip hunter education temporarily and hunt under the supervision of an experienced hunter. More on that below.\n\n## Step 1: Hunter Education\n\n### Who Needs It?\n\nEvery state requires hunter education for first-time license buyers, though the specific rules vary:\n\n| State | Who Must Complete Hunter Ed |\n|-------|----------------------------|\n| Colorado | Everyone born on or after Jan 1, 1949 (effectively all first-timers) |\n| Montana | Everyone born on or after Jan 1, 1985 |\n| Wyoming | Everyone born on or after Jan 1, 1966 |\n| Idaho | Everyone born on or after Jan 1, 1975 who has not previously held a license |\n| Nevada | All first-time hunters |\n| Utah | All first-time license buyers |\n| Arizona | All hunters under 14 for big game; first-timers generally required |\n\n### How to Complete It\n\nYou have three options:\n\n**Online Course** (~$15–$35, 4–8 hours at your own pace)\nThe most popular option. Progress saves between sessions, so you can spread it over several days. The most widely used state-approved provider is hunter-ed.com — it works for all seven western states.\n\n**Hybrid Course** (online study + in-person field day)\nMost states require or strongly recommend a 3–5 hour field day in addition to the online portion. This covers hands-on firearm handling, live-fire exercises, and practical skills that can''t be taught on a screen.\n\n**Traditional In-Person Class** (6–16 hours, often free)\nTaught by volunteer instructors through state wildlife agencies. These are excellent if you want hands-on instruction from the start, and many are offered at no cost.\n\n### The One-Time Rule\n\nHunter education certification is valid for life and accepted in all 50 states and Canada through the International Hunter Education Association (IHEA-USA). You certify once, in any state, and never need to retake it. Keep your card — you will need to show proof when purchasing licenses in new states.\n\n## Step 2: Purchase a Base Hunting License\n\nEvery state requires a base hunting license before you can buy species-specific tags. Here is what it costs:\n\n| State | Resident | Nonresident | Where to Buy |\n|-------|----------|-------------|---------------|\n| Colorado | ~$37 | ~$102 | cpwshop.com |\n| Montana | ~$10 conservation license | ~$60 (conservation + base) | fwp.mt.gov |\n| Wyoming | ~$22 conservation stamp | ~$22 conservation stamp | wgfd.wyo.gov |\n| Idaho | ~$15 | ~$185 | idfg.idaho.gov |\n| Nevada | ~$33 combination | ~$155 combination | ndow.org |\n| Utah | ~$34 | ~$144 | wildlife.utah.gov |\n| Arizona | ~$37 | ~$160 | azgfd.com |\n\nAll states offer online purchasing through their wildlife agency portal. Have your hunter education certificate number ready — you will need it.\n\n### Don''t Forget the Extras\n\nMost states tack on additional mandatory fees:\n- **Colorado**: Habitat stamp (~$12) required for all hunters\n- **Montana**: Conservation license ($10) required before any other purchases\n- **Wyoming**: Conservation stamp ($21.50/year) mandatory for all hunters\n- **Idaho**: Access/depredation fee ($10) on all annual licenses\n\n## Step 3: Get a Tag\n\nA base license gives you permission to hunt. A **tag** gives you permission to harvest a specific animal in a specific area. There are two ways to get one:\n\n### Draw Tags (Apply in Spring, Hunt in Fall)\n\nMost western big game tags are allocated through a lottery. You apply during a window (typically January–April), and the state draws names. If selected, you get a tag. If not, you typically earn a preference or bonus point that improves your odds next year.\n\nApproximate nonresident costs for a deer draw entry (license + tag + fees):\n\n| State | NR Deer (approx.) | NR Elk (approx.) |\n|-------|--------------------|-------------------|\n| Colorado | ~$520 | ~$850 |\n| Montana | ~$775 | ~$1,170 |\n| Wyoming | ~$410 | ~$728 |\n| Idaho | ~$546 | ~$846 |\n| Nevada | ~$405 | ~$1,365 |\n| Utah | ~$743 | ~$993 |\n| Arizona | ~$475 | ~$825 |\n\n### OTC Tags (Buy Anytime)\n\nSome states sell over-the-counter tags for certain species and units — no draw required. Colorado is the most OTC-friendly state for elk, with many units available without a draw. Idaho also offers general deer tags OTC. OTC tags are first-come, first-served and can sell out.\n\n### Your First Year Strategy\n\nDon''t wait for a dream unit. Apply for preference or bonus points in every state you are interested in — time is your most valuable asset. Then pick one realistic hunt: an OTC elk tag in Colorado or a general deer tag in Idaho are great first options.\n\n## The Shortcut: Apprentice and Mentor Programs\n\nIf you want to try hunting before committing to the full hunter education course, most states offer a way:\n\n| State | Program | Cost | Details |\n|-------|---------|------|---------|\n| Colorado | Apprentice Hunter Certificate | Free | One-time use, can obtain twice max. Must hunt with a certified mentor 18+ |\n| Wyoming | Apprentice Hunting License | Varies | Hunt under supervision without completing hunter ed first |\n| Idaho | Hunting Passport | $1.75 | First-time hunters 8+ can try hunting with a licensed adult |\n| Nevada | Apprentice Hunting License | $15 | Must purchase in-person at an NDOW office; mentor must be 18+ with NV license |\n| Arizona | Free Apprentice License | Free | Valid for 2 consecutive days; small game only (not big game) |\n| Montana | No formal program | — | Must complete hunter ed before purchasing |\n| Utah | No formal program | — | Must complete hunter ed before purchasing |\n\nApprentice programs are excellent for adults who are curious about hunting but unsure if they want to commit. You get real field experience under the guidance of someone who knows what they are doing.\n\n## Common First-Timer Mistakes\n\n1. **Missing draw deadlines.** Most western states have spring application windows (January–April) for fall hunts. Miss the window and you wait a full year. Use the Deadline Tracker — that is why we built it.\n\n2. **Not buying points in states you are not hunting yet.** Even if you are not ready to hunt Montana this year, buying a preference point costs relatively little and starts your place in line. Every year you wait, the line gets longer.\n\n3. **Skipping the regulations.** Every state publishes a free regulation booklet on their website that changes annually. Read the General Regulations section before anything else.\n\n4. **Underestimating physical fitness.** Western big game hunts — especially elk in Colorado, Montana, and Wyoming — involve hiking miles in steep terrain at 8,000–12,000 feet. Start training months before your hunt.\n\n5. **Not telling anyone your plan.** Before every hunt, leave a safety itinerary with someone at home: where you will be, when you will return, and when to call for help.\n\n6. **Treating hunter ed as a checkbox.** The course covers essential safety, ethics, and field skills. Take it seriously — it will shape how you hunt for years.\n\n## Next Steps\n\n1. **Complete hunter education.** Go to hunter-ed.com and pick your state. The online portion takes a single afternoon.\n2. **Create accounts** on the wildlife agency portals for every state you are interested in — you will need them for draw applications.\n3. **Open the Deadline Tracker** and mark the application windows for this year. Even if you are not ready to hunt, buying points now starts building your future.\n4. **Find a mentor.** If you do not know experienced hunters, look into state apprentice programs, local hunting clubs, or organizations like Backcountry Hunters & Anglers that run mentorship initiatives.\n5. **Pick one realistic first hunt.** Colorado OTC elk or Idaho general deer are popular first-timer options with accessible public land and available tags.',
  15, 'basic', 'getting-started', 8, true, NOW()
),
(
  'hunting', 'article',
  'Your First Hunt: A Complete Beginner''s Roadmap',
  'first-hunt-roadmap',
  'Everything a brand-new hunter needs to know — from choosing a species and state to what happens after you pull the trigger.',
  E'# Your First Hunt: A Complete Beginner''s Roadmap\n\nYou have your hunter education card. You have a license and a tag. Now what?\n\nThis guide covers everything between "I have a tag" and "I have meat in the freezer" — gear, scouting, the hunt itself, and what happens after the shot. It is written for someone who has never done this before.\n\n## Choosing Your First Hunt\n\nNot all hunts are created equal. Your first hunt should maximize your chances of success while minimizing complexity.\n\n### Best First Species\n\n**Whitetail or Mule Deer** — Deer are the most abundant big game animal in North America. They are accessible on public land, seasons are long, and the learning curve is forgiving. Mule deer in the West tend to be in more open country, making them easier to spot.\n\n**Elk (OTC Colorado)** — Colorado sells over-the-counter elk tags for many units. Elk are harder to hunt than deer — they cover more ground, they are louder, and packing one out is a serious physical effort — but the experience is unmatched. If you are reasonably fit and willing to work, this is the quintessential western hunt.\n\n**Upland Birds (Pheasant, Grouse)** — If big game feels like too much for your first time, start with birds. The gear investment is lower, the physical demand is moderate, and you get more opportunities per day.\n\n### Best First States\n\n- **Colorado** — Most OTC-friendly for elk. Enormous public land base. Well-documented units.\n- **Idaho** — General deer tags available OTC. Diverse terrain and species.\n- **Montana** — Excellent public land access via Block Management. General deer licenses available.\n\n## Essential Gear for Your First Hunt\n\nYou do not need $5,000 worth of equipment. Here is what actually matters:\n\n### The Non-Negotiables\n\n- **Firearm or bow** that you have practiced with extensively. For rifle hunting, a .308 or .30-06 handles all western big game. For archery, a compound bow set at 60–70 lbs.\n- **Ammunition** — bring more than you think you need. Sight in your rifle at 100 and 200 yards before the hunt.\n- **Optics** — binoculars are more important than your rifle. You will spend 90% of your time glassing, not shooting. A decent 10x42 pair is the single best investment you can make.\n- **Boots** — waterproof, broken in, with ankle support. Do not show up in new boots. Break them in over at least 50 miles of hiking before your hunt.\n- **Layers** — western mountain weather can swing 40 degrees in a day. Dress in a moisture-wicking base layer, insulating mid layer, and wind/rain shell. No cotton.\n- **Pack** — a 2,500–3,500 cubic inch daypack for day hunts. If you are camping, you need a frame pack rated for 5,000+ cubic inches that can also haul meat.\n\n### The Almost-Non-Negotiables\n\n- **Rangefinder** — knowing the exact distance to your target eliminates the biggest variable in shot placement.\n- **Headlamp** — you will be hiking in the dark. Bring extra batteries.\n- **GPS or mapping app** — onX Hunt or similar, with offline maps downloaded for your area.\n- **Game bags** — lightweight breathable bags to protect meat from dirt and flies during pack-out. Do not use garbage bags.\n- **Knife** — a sharp, simple fixed-blade knife for field dressing. Bring a sharpener.\n\n### What You Do NOT Need (Yet)\n\n- A $3,000 custom rifle. A clean, well-maintained hunting rifle in good caliber will kill any animal in North America.\n- A ghillie suit or full camo system. Earth-toned clothing that does not make noise works fine.\n- Scent-eliminating sprays and gadgets. Playing the wind matters 100 times more than any spray.\n- A $600 GPS unit. Your phone with onX and an offline map is sufficient. Carry a backup battery.\n\n## Scouting Before the Season\n\nShowing up opening day without prior knowledge of your unit is a significant disadvantage. Even a few hours of digital scouting makes a difference.\n\n### Digital Scouting (Free)\n\n1. **Study the unit boundary** on onX or Google Earth. Identify public vs. private land.\n2. **Find water sources** — creeks, springs, stock tanks. Animals visit water daily, especially in arid western terrain.\n3. **Look for transition zones** — where timber meets meadow, where ridgelines drop into basins. These edges concentrate animal movement.\n4. **Check elevation** — in early season, animals tend to be higher. As snow pushes them down through the season, lower elevations become productive.\n5. **Read hunt reports** — forums like Rokslide, iSportsman, and state-specific Facebook groups have firsthand accounts from people who have hunted your unit.\n\n### Boots-on-the-Ground Scouting\n\nIf you can visit your unit before the season, even for a day:\n\n- **Glass from high points** at dawn and dusk. Animals move in low light.\n- **Look for sign** — tracks, droppings, rubs (on trees), wallows (for elk). Fresh sign tells you animals are using the area now.\n- **Note access points** — where can you park? What trails lead into the unit? How far is the walk to where you want to hunt?\n- **Talk to locals** — ranch supply stores, gas stations, and campground hosts in small western towns can be surprisingly helpful.\n\n## The Hunt Itself\n\n### The Daily Rhythm\n\nBig game animals are most active in the first and last two hours of daylight. A typical day:\n\n- **4:30 AM** — Wake up. Eat. Dress. Pack your daypack.\n- **5:00 AM** — Hike to your glassing point or hunting area. You want to be in position before shooting light.\n- **5:30–9:00 AM** — Prime time. Glass methodically. Move slowly. The animal will almost always see, hear, or smell you before you see it.\n- **9:00 AM–3:00 PM** — Midday lull. Animals bed down. Use this time to eat, rest, scout new areas, or still-hunt through timber.\n- **3:00–Last Light** — Second prime window. Animals feed again. Get back to a glassing point.\n\n### The Three Rules of Not Getting Busted\n\n1. **Wind is everything.** Always approach from downwind. Animals smell you from hundreds of yards away. Check the wind constantly — a puff of powder, a lighter flame, or even dust tossed in the air tells you the direction.\n2. **Move slowly.** Human movement patterns — upright posture, steady pace, rhythmic steps — are instantly recognizable to wildlife. Stop frequently. Glass before you move.\n3. **Be quiet.** Avoid stepping on dry branches. Do not slam truck doors at the trailhead in the dark. Whisper to your hunting partner. Silence is not optional.\n\n## After the Shot\n\nThis is where many first-time hunters feel unprepared. Know the process before you need it.\n\n### Immediately After\n\n1. **Mark the time and the animal''s last known location.** Use your GPS to drop a pin.\n2. **Wait.** If the animal ran, give it 30 minutes before following (longer for a marginal hit). Pushing a wounded animal makes recovery harder.\n3. **Follow the blood trail.** Mark each blood sign with flagging tape or toilet paper so you can retrace if you lose the trail.\n\n### Field Dressing\n\nField dressing is the process of removing the internal organs to cool the meat as quickly as possible. It is messy but straightforward:\n\n1. Place the animal on its back, belly up.\n2. Cut from the pelvic bone to the sternum, cutting through the skin and abdominal wall. Be careful not to puncture the stomach or intestines.\n3. Reach in and pull the organs out in one mass. Cut the diaphragm where it attaches to the ribcage.\n4. Cut the windpipe and esophagus at the base of the neck.\n5. Roll the animal to drain blood.\n6. Prop the body cavity open with a stick to promote air circulation and cooling.\n\nWatch a video before your hunt. There are excellent step-by-step field dressing tutorials on YouTube from MeatEater, Randy Newberg, and state wildlife agencies. Watching one 15-minute video removes most of the anxiety.\n\n### Getting the Meat Out\n\nThis is the hardest part of a western hunt — physically harder than the hunt itself.\n\n- **Quartering**: If you cannot drive to the animal, you will need to quarter it (separate it into four leg quarters, backstraps, tenderloins, neck meat, and rib meat) and pack it out in game bags.\n- **Weight**: A boned-out mule deer is roughly 60–80 lbs of meat. A bull elk is 150–200+ lbs. Plan multiple trips or bring a hunting partner.\n- **Meat care**: Get the meat into shade and airflow immediately. Hang quarters in game bags from a tree if you need to make multiple trips. In warm early-season weather, getting the meat cool is a race against spoilage.\n\n### Tagging and Reporting\n\nBefore you move the animal:\n1. **Validate your tag** — notch or punch the date.\n2. **Attach the tag** to the carcass.\n3. **Report your harvest** within the state''s required window (as short as 48 hours in Nevada and Utah).\n\n## The Unwritten Rules\n\nThese are not in any regulation booklet, but experienced hunters live by them:\n\n- **Respect other hunters'' space.** If someone is set up in an area, do not crowd them. Find your own spot.\n- **Recover your animal.** Do everything in your power to find a wounded animal. If you cannot, report it to a game warden — they can help and they will respect your honesty.\n- **Use all the meat.** Wanton waste is illegal in every western state, but even beyond the law — you owe it to the animal to use what it gave.\n- **Thank the landowner.** If you hunted private land or a walk-in access property, a thank-you note or a gift of processed meat goes a long way toward keeping that access open for future hunters.\n- **Bring someone new next time.** The hunting community grows one mentor at a time. Once you know how, pass it on.\n\n## Next Steps\n\n1. If you have not gotten your license yet, read "How to Get Your First Hunting License" in this course library.\n2. Pick a state and unit. Use the Deadline Tracker to see what''s open.\n3. Start a gear list — prioritize optics, boots, and layers over everything else.\n4. Watch field dressing videos before you need the skill.\n5. Find a hunting partner or mentor. Your first hunt is better with someone who has done it before.',
  15, 'basic', 'getting-started', 9, true, NOW()
);
